### **IMAP vs POP3**

- **IMAP (Internet Message Access Protocol)**
    
    - Access emails from server, manage emails online.
        
    - Supports folders and hierarchical mailbox structures.
        
    - Client-server-based; allows local email client to sync with server mailbox.
        
    - Multiple clients can sync with same mailbox; emails stay on server until deleted.
        
    - Text-based (ASCII commands), extended functions (browse server emails).
        
    - Requires active connection, some clients offer offline mode with sync on reconnect.
        
    - Default port: 143 (unencrypted), 993 (SSL/TLS).
        
- **POP3 (Post Office Protocol v3)**
    
    - Only lists, retrieves, and deletes emails.
        
    - No folder management or multiple mailbox access.
        
    - Default port: 110 (unencrypted), 995 (SSL/TLS).
        
- **Security**
    
    - IMAP/POP3 unencrypted transmits credentials in plain text.
        
    - SSL/TLS used for encryption, standard/alternative ports depending on implementation.
        
- **SMTP**
    
    - Usually used to send emails.
        
    - Copying sent emails to IMAP folder allows all clients to access sent mails.
        
- **Advantages of IMAP**
    
    - Personal folders/folder structures for better management.
        
    - Multi-user access simultaneously.
        
    - Synchronization across multiple clients.
        
- **Disadvantages**
    
    - Increased server storage.
        
    - Offline management requires local mailbox copy.
        

